SIMPLE: observance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Observance
<hw>Ob*serv"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>observance</ets>, L. <ets>observantia</ets>. See
<er>Observant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or practice of
observing or noticing with attention; a heeding or keeping with care;
performance; -- usually with a sense of strictness and fidelity; <as>as,
the <ex>observance</ex> of the Sabbath is general; the strict
<ex>observance</ex> of duties.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a custom⟦br⟧
More honored in the breach than the <qex>observance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An act, ceremony, or rite, as of worship or respect;
especially, a customary act or service of attention; a form; a practice;
a rite; a custom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At dances⟦br⟧
These young folk kept their <qex>observances</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Use all the <qex>observance</qex> of civility.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some represent to themselves the whole of religion as consisting
in a few easy <qex>observances</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O I that wasted time to tend upon her,⟦br⟧
To compass her with sweet <qex>observances</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Servile attention; sycophancy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Salads and flesh, such as their haste could get,⟦br⟧
Served with <qex>observance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is not atheism,⟦br⟧
But court <qex>observance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Observance</er>, <er>Observation</er>. These
words are discriminated by the two distinct senses of
<xex>observe</xex>. To <xex>observe</xex> means (1) to keep strictly;
as, to <xex>observe</xex> a fast day, and hence, <xex>observance</xex>
denotes the keeping or heeding with strictness; (2) to consider
attentively, or to remark; and hence, <xex>observation</xex> denotes
either the act of <xex>observing</xex>, or some remark made as the
result thereof. We do not say the <xex>observation</xex> of Sunday,
though the word was formerly so used. The Pharisees were curious in
external <xex>observances</xex>; the astronomers are curious in
celestial <xex>observations</xex>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love rigid honesty,⟦br⟧
And strict <qex>observance</qex> of impartial laws.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Observancy</ent>⟦br⟧
